(142, 1, '2021-01-22 09:57:59', '2021-01-22 09:57:59', '<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\nOver the last few weeks, I have spent some time learning about how to improve my <a href=\"https://www.jonniegrieve.co.uk\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" aria-label=\"website\'s front end performance (opens in a new tab)\">website\'s front end performance</a> i.e. the speed in which all assets load in an effort to retain visitors and hopefully even improve my search ranking.\r\n\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\nThis involves looking at the number of requests I\'m making\r\nto my server, how my images and web files are optimised, how I can make savings\r\nand even how the code is rendered.\r\n\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\nAt the start of this process, I had a look at the figures via <strong>ChromeDev</strong> Tools. They tally up the resources, HTTP Requests and bandwidth used and this is the crux of where I started out with.\r\n\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:quote -->\r\n<blockquote class=\"wp-block-quote\"><strong>38 requests -  134 KB transferred  - 2.2 MB resources - Finish: 1.67 </strong>\r\n\r\n<cite>first check</cite></blockquote>\r\n<!-- /wp:quote -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\nIt\'s worth pointing out at this point that some of these numbers are network dependent and some are finite. It shows that as of a few weeks ago (October 2019), I was serving up to <strong>2.2MB</strong> of data, only <strong>134kb</strong> of which I was actually choosing to render in the HTML. So not exactly the most bandwidth straining of websites, but this is deliberately so. And it\'s not necessarily the case that this means a 100% speedy experience but again that depends on what your network speed is.\r\n\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\nFinally, after a brief check, there did not appear to be any unused assets so no HTTP 404 errors were returned and no wasted resources.\r\n\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:heading -->\r\n<h2>Optimising images</h2>\r\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\nMost of the 2.2mb total consists of images that were simply not optimised. Indeed the design includes a main background image that is fixed on scroll that I edited a little bit on Photoshop and exported as an image file with barely a second thought to optimisation.\r\n\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\nLet\'s look at the main background image as an example.\r\n\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:quote -->\r\n<blockquote class=\"wp-block-quote\"><em>interior-darker.png  - 1,739.kb\r\nimg/ios-bg.png   - 14kb</em></blockquote>\r\n<!-- /wp:quote -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\nSo those background images on their own represented the vast majority of the resources I was using.  So what could be done to reduce that load?\r\n\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\nI went back into Photoshop and opened the image up and exported the file using \"save for web\". Using this, I saved a copy of the image with a 60% quality level with progressive download style and this time I saved it as a jpeg.\r\n\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n4,323,001 bytes reduced to 473,322kb  (a saving of 3,849,679 bytes) 4,323,001  - 3,849,679 is an <strong>89.05%</strong> saving\r\n\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\nAn 89% saving just on the background image served alone.\r\n\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:quote -->\r\n<blockquote class=\"wp-block-quote\"><strong>35 requests  129 KB transferred  2.1 MB resources  Finish: 2.01 s    </strong>\r\n\r\n<cite>The latest savings</cite></blockquote>\r\n<!-- /wp:quote -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:heading -->\r\n<h2>SVG Sprite Maps</h2>\r\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\nThe \"Service\" section images on my <a href=\"https://www.jonniegrieve.co.uk\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" aria-label=\"website (opens in a new tab)\">website</a> are served via a font <strong>Content Delivery Network (CDN)</strong>. So these are not images that could have been easily targeted to reduce resources. I wanted to see if there was a way to serve some of my service icons the same sprite map but these are fonts rather than SVG\'s but that\'s not the case.  I was, however, able to use SVG for social media icons.\r\n\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\nUsing this method I created a sprite map of several\r\ncontained SVG’s in one resource so only one HTTP Request was taken up.\r\n\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:quote -->\r\n<blockquote class=\"wp-block-quote\"><strong>31 requests  156 KB transferred  1.1 MB resources Finish: 1.51 s  Load: 1.52 s</strong>\r\n\r\n<cite>Performance Savings: Round 3</cite></blockquote>\r\n<!-- /wp:quote -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\nHaving looked at my main background images and social media\r\nicons I then turned my attention to the rest of the images and how they could\r\nbe optimised. Most of my images are stored in directories according to their\r\nintended use.  As I began the process,\r\nthis is the total size of each directory.\r\n\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<em>Featured directory:  2.4mb\r\nServices directory:  200kb</em>\r\n\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\nThese were all <strong>.PNG</strong> files. I switched the majority of PNG\'s now from PNG to JPG using the same export settings for the main background image (60% quality compared to the PNG\'S and progressive download).  The result of this was that resources and transfers now <strong>total less than 1mb</strong>.\r\n\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<em>Featured directory: 992 KB (1,015,808 bytes)\r\nServices Directory:  135kb</em>\r\n\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:quote -->\r\n<blockquote class=\"wp-block-quote\"><strong>31 requests 754 KB transferred  993 KB resources  Finish: 2.39 s  Load: 1.77 s</strong></blockquote>\r\n<!-- /wp:quote -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\nSo, for the first time the resources show up as taking less than a 1mb in served resources. Great!\r\n\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\nThere is a video asset in this website. Videos typically take up more bandwidth than image files whether they are served by an external CDN or not. I made the decision to stick to an HTML5 video tag rather than embedding a YouTube link. I may investigate further but for now, the video takes up the bandwidth.\r\n\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:heading -->\r\n<h2>Minifying the JavaScript and CSS</h2>\r\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\nMinifying files is the process of reducing the file size of CSS and JS assets by stripping out comments and any spaces in the code. Typically this is done using a build tool which can add to the website payload, but since this is only a small website, I opted to use online tools to minify my files.\r\n\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\nMinifying files like this saved me a further <strong>6kb</strong> which is a minimal benefit in this case but I felt it only right to do it.\r\n\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:quote -->\r\n<blockquote class=\"wp-block-quote\"><strong>34 requests 739 KB transferred 859 KB resources Finish: 4.25 s Load: 3.71 s</strong>\r\n\r\n<cite>Last check. - remember some of these results are network dependent</cite></blockquote>\r\n<!-- /wp:quote -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:heading -->\r\n<h2>Resizes and Compressed Images</h2>\r\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\nThe last thing I want to talk about is the process of image display resolution. Display resolution refers to how devices display images in their browsers. Correctly sizing and compressing images can help save a little space but is also an important consideration for retina display devices.  Delivering images that are appropriately compressed and sized to their container will reduce file sizes, otherwise, it is wasted bandwidth.\r\n\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\nThe theory is that by halving the size of the image when you export the file reduces the number of pixels that need to be displayed by the time it is shown in the browser.\r\n\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\nSo when you start exporting in your image editor:\r\n\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:list -->\r\n<ul>\r\n 	<li>1024 by 768 becomes</li>\r\n 	<li>532 by 399   (twice the resolution)</li>\r\n 	<li>266 by 200 pixels</li>\r\n 	<li>Natural 532 by 399</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<!-- /wp:list -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\nSo the pixels rendered should be showing reduced compared to natural/intrinsic value. But as of the day of posting this blog, this is not happening for me.\r\n\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\nSo I\'m going to look at this further but for now I\'m happy with the performance savings I have so far made.  I’ve reduced the bandwidth by more than half and significantly increased my website speed.  I’ve learned a lot during this process and the techniques I\'ve learned in this blog are standard I intend to follow going forward.\r\n\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->', 'A Learning Process: Front End Performance Optimisation', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '102-revision-v1', '', '', '2021-01-22 09:57:59', '2021-01-22 09:57:59', '', 102, 'http://localhost/wordpress/subdomain/2021/01/22/102-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
